docs.lead_paragraph: Patricia Bosworth writes frequently about people in the arts. This article is adapted from her biography ''Diane Arbus,'' to be published next month by Knopf. AS A TEEN-AGER, DIANE Arbus used to stand on the window ledge of her parents' New York apartment in the San Remo, high above Central Park West. She would stand there on the ledge for as long as she could, gazing out at the trees and skyscrapers in the distance, until her mother pulled her back inside. Years later, Diane would say: ''I wanted to see if I could do it.'' And she would add: ''I didn't inherit my kingdom for a long time.''

headline.main: DIANE ARBUS, HER VISION, LIDE, AND DEATH
